Boil a large #pot of salted water for the @dried rigatoni{180%g}.

When boiling, add the rigatoni to the water and bring back to the boil.

Cook until softened, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander and pop back in the pot. Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}.

Coarsely grate the @carrot{1}.

Halve the @cherry tomatoes{125%g}.

Pick and roughly tear the @basil{10%g} leaves.

Place a large #pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Add the onion to the #pan and fry until softened, stirring occasionally, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add the carrot and @Irish beef mince{250%g} and fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon to break it up as it cooks.

Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Add the halved tomatoes to the mince and cook for a further ~{2-3%minutes}.

Reduce heat to low, pour in the @chopped tomatoes{1%pack} with @sugar{1%tbsp}.

Stir everything together and simmer for ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

After simmering, toss the cooked pasta and half the torn basil leaves into the sauce.

Sprinkle the @grated cheese{50%g} over the pasta.

Cover and continue to simmer for ~{1%minute}, until the cheese has melted slightly.

Divide the pasta between bowls.

Garnish with the remaining basil.